__d(function(g,r,i,a,m,e,d){"use strict";Object.defineProperty(e,'__esModule',{value:!0}),Object.defineProperty(e,"COCKTAIL_HISTORY",{enumerable:!0,get:function(){return t}});const t=[{id:"golden-age",name:"The Golden Age",period:"1800s-1910s",icon:"\ud83c\udfa9",summary:"The era when bartending became a craft, cocktails were systematized, and the foundation of modern mixology was established.",content:"The Golden Age of cocktails emerged in the mid-1800s when bartending transformed from simple pouring into something approaching an art form. This was the era of the professional bartender\u2014\"Professor\" bartenders who guarded their recipes jealously and built reputations on their skill. The first printed cocktail recipes appeared in this period, most notably in Jerry Thomas's seminal 1862 work, \"How to Mix Drinks, or the Bon Vivant's Companion,\" which is often considered the first professional bartender's guide ever published.\n\nJerry Thomas, known as the \"Professor,\" is arguably the most important figure in cocktail history. He wasn't just a bartender; he was a celebrity, a showman, and a systematizer. He traveled the world, worked in famous establishments, and documented cocktail recipes at a time when most bartenders considered their recipes proprietary secrets. His book legitimized bartending as a profession and created the first standard recipes for classic cocktails like the Old Fashioned, the Martini, and the Manhattan. Thomas understood that cocktails weren't random mixtures but carefully balanced formulas, and his work elevated the entire profession.\n\nThe Old Fashioned, which emerged during this period, is perhaps the perfect symbol of the Golden Age. It's the original cocktail\u2014spirit, sugar, bitters, water, ice\u2014stripped down to its essentials and balanced to perfection. The drink requires skill to make correctly; it demands understanding of dilution, balance, and technique. In many ways, mastering the Old Fashioned is mastering the entire philosophy of the Golden Age: that cocktails should be spirit-forward, properly diluted, and balanced through technique rather than through complexity.\n\nThis era also saw the rise of the cocktail bar as an institution. Famous establishments like the Waldorf-Astoria, the Delmonico's Bar, and Jerry Thomas's own bars became destinations for anyone serious about drinking well. These weren't clubs or restaurants with bars attached; they were temples of cocktail craft. Bartenders were celebrated, their methods were discussed and debated, and the standards for what made a good cocktail were being established.",keyDrinks:["old-fashioned","manhattan","martini","sazerac"],keyFigures:["Jerry Thomas","Harry Craddock"],keyInnovation:"The professionalization and systematization of bartending; the first published cocktail recipes and professional bar guides; the concept of the cocktail as a balanced formula rather than random mixture"},{id:"prohibition",name:"Prohibition & the Speakeasy Era",period:"1920-1933",icon:"\ud83e\udd43",summary:"The era when American cocktail culture was nearly destroyed by law, forcing innovation and adaptation\u2014and creating some of the most creative cocktails ever invented.",content:"Prohibition was a disaster for American cocktail culture. When the 18th Amendment made the production and sale of alcohol illegal in 1920, the entire infrastructure of American bartending collapsed overnight. The great bars closed, professional bartenders were suddenly unemployable, and the quality of available spirits plummeted. The bootleggers and smugglers who supplied speakeasies and illegal bars cared nothing for quality; they cut spirits with water, mixed bathtub gin, and produced brandy and rum that was often toxic.\n\nBut necessity breeds invention. Because the spirits available during Prohibition were so terrible\u2014harsh, rough, undrinkable neat\u2014bartenders were forced to be creative. They couldn't rely on quality ingredients, so they invented cocktails that masked the horrible flavor of cheap, cut spirits. The Daiquiri, the Sidecar, the Cosmopolitan-style drinks with heavy citrus and sugar to hide the rough booze\u2014these cocktails were born from desperation. Ironically, many of these \"mask the bad liquor\" cocktails became classics that survive today, though modern versions are made with quality spirits rather than bootleg swill.\n\nProhibition also scattered American bartenders across the globe. Many fled to Europe\u2014Paris, London, Berlin\u2014where they established bars and continued their craft. Others went to Cuba and the Caribbean, where rum was still freely available and American tourists with money could still find a decent drink. This diaspora actually enriched the global cocktail scene; American bartending influence spread worldwide, and European and Caribbean techniques filtered back to influence American bartenders who remained (or returned after Repeal).\n\nThe Savoy Hotel in London became a sort of exile community for American bartenders during Prohibition. The Savoy's bartenders, many of them Americans who'd fled the United States, created some of the most enduring cocktails of this era. Harry Craddock, the Savoy's head bartender, published \"The Savoy Cocktail Book\" in 1930, a comprehensive guide documenting hundreds of cocktails and establishing standards that influence bartenders to this day.\n\nSpeakeasies themselves became cultural institutions\u2014illegal bars hidden behind unmarked doors, accessible only to people who knew the right person or said the right password. They were glamorous and dangerous, and they attracted a different crowd than the old bars had. The Golden Age bars were mostly gentlemen's establishments; speakeasies were more democratic, attracting artists, writers, musicians, and socialites looking for excitement and transgression.\n\nWhen Prohibition ended in 1933, American bartending had to rebuild from rubble. The knowledge had been dispersed, the professional infrastructure was gone, and many of the old bars never reopened. But the cocktails that survived Prohibition\u2014the ones that were good even when made with bootleg spirits\u2014became the modern canon of classic cocktails. In a dark way, Prohibition created the cocktails we still drink today.",keyDrinks:["daiquiri","sidecar","cosmopolitan"],keyFigures:["Harry Craddock","Exiled American bartenders in Europe and Cuba"],keyInnovation:"Cocktails designed to mask low-quality spirits; the global dispersal of American bartending knowledge; the codification of cocktail recipes in Harry Craddock's Savoy book; the cultural mythology of speakeasies as glamorous transgression"},{id:"tiki-era",name:"The Tiki Era",period:"1930s-1960s",icon:"\ud83c\udf3a",summary:"The explosion of tropical escapism and rum-focused creativity that reinvented cocktail culture as entertainment, spectacle, and imagination.",content:"The Tiki era emerged during the Great Depression and flourished through the post-World War II period as a response to economic hardship and the desire for escapism. In 1933, Don the Beachcomber (Ernest Beaumont Gantt) opened his first tiki bar in Los Angeles, inspired by Caribbean and Polynesian aesthetics. Don's genius was understanding that people didn't just want a drink; they wanted an experience, an escape, a fantasy of tropical paradise. His bars featured bamboo d\xe9cor, exotic masks and statues, tiki-style glassware, and most importantly, an entirely new category of cocktails built around rum and elaborate presentation.\n\nDon the Beachcomber's innovation was the rum-focused cocktail, often built from multiple rums blended together and combined with fresh fruit juices, syrups, and spices. His most famous creation, the Mai Tai, became the defining cocktail of the era\u2014though its origins are disputed and have sparked decades of argument among tiki enthusiasts. Trader Vic (Victor Jules Bergeron), who opened his own Polynesian restaurant and bar in the 1930s, became Tiki's other great innovator. Trader Vic and Don the Beachcomber built competing empires of tiki bars and restaurants, each claiming to have invented the Mai Tai, each pushing the boundaries of what a tropical cocktail could be.\n\nThe Tiki era represented the original craft cocktail movement, even though nobody called it that at the time. Bartenders were obsessed with quality ingredients\u2014fresh lime and lemon juice, fresh pineapple juice, cream of coconut, complex syrups. They experimented with rum blending, combining two, three, or even four different rums in a single drink to create layers of flavor and complexity. The presentation was theatrical and elaborate: drinks served in ceramic tiki mugs, garnished with fresh pineapple, orchids, and elaborate arrangements of fruit. The experience was immersive\u2014you didn't just drink; you traveled to an imagined paradise.\n\nThe Mai Tai is the central symbol of this era. Don and Trader Vic both claimed to have invented it, and the debate continues to this day. What matters more than who invented it is what the Mai Tai represents: rum blended for complexity, fresh citrus, quality ingredients, and a commitment to craft. The classic version features light rum and aged rum, lime juice, orgeat, and a float of Jamaican rum on top. It's a drink that could not have been created without the innovations and obsessions of the Tiki era.\n\nThe Tiki era also brought frozen drinks, tropical fruit-based cocktails, and the concept of the cocktail as visual spectacle. Bartenders experimented with crushed ice, elaborate presentations, and the theatrical use of fire (flaming garnishes, flaming drinks). Some of this was kitsch, some of it was genuine craft, and the best tiki bars and bartenders managed to be both simultaneously\u2014entertaining and excellent.\n\nBy the 1960s, Tiki culture had become mainstream enough to seem dated to younger drinkers. The aesthetics that had felt exotic and escapist in the 1940s felt tired and kitschy by the 1960s. The pendulum swung away from Tiki, and tropical cocktails became associated with cheap, mass-produced drinks and low-quality spirits. It took decades for Tiki to be revived and appreciated as a serious, sophisticated form of cocktail craft.",keyDrinks:["mai-tai","zombie","hurricane","painkiller"],keyFigures:["Don the Beachcomber","Trader Vic"],keyInnovation:"Rum blending for complexity; fresh juices and quality ingredients in tropical cocktails; the cocktail as theatrical presentation and immersive experience; the concept of the tiki bar as destination and escape fantasy; frozen cocktails and crushed-ice presentations"},{id:"dark-ages",name:"The Dark Ages",period:"1970s-1990s",icon:"\ud83c\udf19",summary:"The era when cocktail culture reached its nadir\u2014cheap ingredients, artificial mixes, and the near-extinction of bartending craft.",content:"The 1970s through 1990s were genuinely dark times for cocktail culture. The decline had started in the 1960s, but by the 1970s it was in full swing. Quality spirits became expensive while sour mix and pre-made cocktail bases became cheap and ubiquitous. Chain restaurants and hotels standardized their drink menus using commercial mixes, processed fruit juices, and bottom-shelf spirits. The concept of the craft bartender disappeared, replaced by bartenders who were essentially vending machines\u2014they could make a Daiquiri if you asked, but they'd make it from sour mix and cheap rum, producing something closer to a flavored slurpee than a cocktail.\n\nThe Cosmopolitan, invented in the 1980s, is a perfect symbol of this era. It's not a bad cocktail\u2014a well-made Cosmo with quality vodka, Cointreau, fresh lime juice, and cranberry juice is actually quite good. But the Cosmo was also the poster child for the degradation of cocktail standards. It was ubiquitous in bars, it was often made badly (with sour mix instead of lime juice, with artificial cranberry \"juice\"), and it became the archetypal cocktail of the era\u2014colorful, sweet, designed more for marketing than for flavor. When bartenders saw someone order a Cosmo, they didn't think \"craft cocktail\"; they thought \"easy drink for someone who doesn't know what they're doing.\"\n\nThe Long Island Iced Tea, created in the 1970s, is another emblematic drink of the Dark Ages. It's a monstrosity\u2014seven different spirits, three liqueurs, sour mix, sweet & sour mix, cola\u2014designed to pack as much alcohol into one drink as possible while tasting as little like alcohol as possible. It's the opposite of balance, the opposite of craft, the opposite of everything the Golden Age and Tiki era stood for. Yet it became hugely popular, especially in chain bars and tourist destinations.\n\nThis era saw the rise of theme restaurants and casual dining chains, which devastated local bar culture. Olive Garden, Applebee's, TGI Friday's\u2014these establishments employed bartenders trained in corporate-standardized recipes using commercial mixes. The restaurants printed their recipes in binders, and bartenders followed them exactly. There was no innovation, no craft, no understanding of why a cocktail was balanced the way it was. You couldn't ask for something slightly different; you got what was in the manual.\n\nThe spirits industry also suffered. Bourbon, rye, and quality spirits fell out of fashion in favor of vodka, which was marketed as \"pure\" and \"neutral.\" The idea that a quality spirit should have flavor and character became almost radical. Vodka's neutrality was presented as a virtue, and cocktails were designed around mixers and juices rather than around spirits. Quality bartenders watched this happen with horror, but they were increasingly irrelevant\u2014the market had moved on.\n\nDuring this nadir, the knowledge of cocktail craft nearly disappeared. The old bartenders who'd learned from Jerry Thomas's successors retired without passing on their knowledge. Books on cocktail technique went out of print. The cocktail was reduced to a vehicle for whatever marketing gimmick or trend was popular\u2014neon-colored drinks, shots, J\xe4gerbombs, and other indignities. The word \"cocktail\" meant something entirely different in 1990 than it had meant in 1910.",keyDrinks:["cosmopolitan","long-island-iced-tea"],keyFigures:["Corporate bartenders, chain restaurant beverage directors"],keyInnovation:"Commercial sour mix and pre-made cocktail bases; industrial-scale standardization; marketing-driven drink creation; the complete divorce of bartending from craft and expertise"},{id:"craft-revival",name:"The Craft Revival",period:"2000s-2010s",icon:"\ud83c\udf93",summary:"The rediscovery of pre-Prohibition cocktails, the rise of skilled bartenders as professionals, and the resurrection of bartending as a serious craft.",content:"The Craft Revival began quietly in the early 2000s, driven by a handful of bartenders who were obsessed with cocktail history and quality. These were people who'd read old cocktail books, studied Jerry Thomas and Harry Craddock, and decided that the Dark Ages of sour mix and artificial juices needed to end. They started making cocktails from scratch\u2014fresh lime juice squeezed by hand, simple syrup made in their own kitchens, quality spirits selected carefully rather than ordered from whatever distributor was cheapest.\n\nDale DeGroff, often called the \"King of Cocktails,\" was one of the central figures of this revival. DeGroff had worked in theme restaurants during the Dark Ages but became obsessed with cocktail history and technique. He began studying old recipes, experimenting with techniques, and pushing back against the standardization and mediocrity he saw in commercial bartending. His book \"The Craft of the Cocktail,\" published in 2002, became a manifesto for the revival\u2014it documented pre-Prohibition recipes, explained technique and theory, and made the case that bartending could be an art form worthy of serious study.\n\nSasha Petraske, who opened Milk & Honey in New York in 2000, became the symbol of a different strain of the revival. Milk & Honey was deliberately obscure\u2014no sign on the door, hidden location, no cocktail menu. You arrived, told the bartender what spirits and flavors you liked, and they made something for you. This was bartending as craft, as conversation, as collaboration. Milk & Honey became the most influential bar of the 2000s because it rejected everything the Dark Ages had stood for: it had no marketing, no artificial sweetness, no commercial mixes, no theme. It was just excellent cocktails made with care and intention.\n\nDeath & Co, which opened in New York in 2006, brought the speakeasy aesthetic and serious craft cocktails to a venue that was more accessible than Milk & Honey. Death & Co became famous for their house cocktails\u2014they created new drinks alongside classics, and they trained their bartenders to understand not just recipes but principles: dilution, balance, how different spirits behave, how to taste and adjust. They published a book, \"Death & Co: Modern Cocktails,\" that influenced a generation of bartenders.\n\nThe Craft Revival also meant returning to fresh ingredients and understanding what mattered: fresh-squeezed lime and lemon juice, house-made syrups and bitters, quality spirits, proper technique. It meant small ice, proper dilution, and understanding why a drink was balanced the way it was. Bartenders began studying books, tasting spirits intentionally, and practicing techniques until they became second nature. The speakeasy revival\u2014bars with no signs, hidden locations, emphasis on craft and craftsmanship\u2014became the aesthetic and practical model for the best bars.\n\nThis era also saw the rise of bartending competitions and professional organizations. The World Class competition, the Diageo World Class competition, and others created forums where bartenders could showcase skill and innovation. These competitions drove standards upward and created a sense of bartending as a profession with real expertise and standards.\n\nBy the 2010s, the Craft Revival had won. Quality spirits were cool again, fresh juice was standard, and the idea that a bartender should understand dilution and balance was no longer radical. Young bartenders came up in this era learning from people who'd studied cocktail history and understood technique. The knowledge that had nearly disappeared during the Dark Ages was being recovered and transmitted to new generations.",keyDrinks:["daiquiri","manhattan","negroni","old-fashioned"],keyFigures:["Dale DeGroff","Sasha Petraske","Death & Co bartenders","Pegu Club team"],keyInnovation:"Fresh juices and house-made ingredients; the return to pre-Prohibition recipes and techniques; the speakeasy aesthetic and hidden-location bars; bartending competitions and professional standards; the concept of bartending as a serious craft profession"},{id:"modern-era",name:"The Modern Era",period:"2010s-Present",icon:"\ud83d\udd2c",summary:"The current age of experimentation, sustainability, and democratization\u2014where cocktail craft continues to evolve while becoming more accessible globally.",content:"The Modern Era builds on the Craft Revival's foundation while pushing in new directions. The core principles\u2014fresh juice, quality spirits, understanding dilution and balance\u2014are now baseline standards at any bar that considers itself serious. But modern bartenders are also innovating in ways that would have been unthinkable even 10 years ago.\n\nThe low-ABV movement has been significant. Rather than assuming that cocktails need to be spirit-heavy and powerful, modern bartenders are exploring drinks with lower alcohol content but equal complexity. Aperol Spritz, which seemed like a curiosity in 2005, is now ubiquitous. Vermouth-forward cocktails and wine-based aperitifs have become cool. Bartenders are exploring how to build balance and complexity without relying on high-proof spirits as the foundation.\n\nMezcal's explosion is another defining feature of the modern era. Tequila was always part of cocktail culture, but mezcal was relatively unknown outside Mexico until the 2010s. The smoky, complex character of mezcal opened entirely new possibilities for cocktail creation. Mezcal cocktails have become a category unto themselves, with bartenders pushing to understand how mezcal's smoky character interacts with other ingredients.\n\nTechnical innovation has also defined this era. Clarified cocktails\u2014drinks that look transparent but contain all the flavor of a cloudy drink\u2014became possible through new techniques like centrifugation and clarification with milk or oil. Fat-washing, where a spirit is infused with fat from bacon or butter, became a legitimate technique used in restaurants and bars. Spherification, where cocktail ingredients are transformed into liquid-filled spheres, made an appearance. Some of these techniques are gimmicks, some are genuinely useful, but they represent the ongoing experimentation and innovation that defines modern bartending.\n\nSustainability has become an explicit concern. Bartenders are thinking about waste, about using whole fruits and vegetables rather than throwing away parts, about sourcing spirits responsibly. Some bars have moved to all-house-made ingredients; others have created zero-waste programs. This ties back to the original principles of craft\u2014caring about quality and intent extends to caring about impact.\n\nThe democratization of good drinks has been perhaps the most important shift. In the Craft Revival era, great cocktails were available only at high-end bars in major cities. Now, knowledge is available to anyone with an internet connection. Home bartenders can access the same books, the same techniques, the same ingredient knowledge as professional bartenders. The gap between home bartending and professional bartending has narrowed dramatically. This hasn't killed professional bartending; instead, it's raised the baseline of what bartenders are expected to know and be able to do.\n\nGlobally, bartending has diversified. The American cocktail tradition is now one tradition among many. Bartenders in Europe, Asia, and other regions are developing their own cocktail cultures, drawing on local spirits and ingredients while engaging with the global cocktail conversation. A Japanese bartender might be exploring whisky cocktails using Japanese whisky; a Mexican bartender might be creating innovative mezcal drinks; a Scandinavian bartender might be exploring aquavit-based creations.\n\nThe Modern Era is still ongoing, and its definitive characteristics are still being written. But it's clear that cocktail culture is now robust enough to sustain multiple approaches simultaneously: traditional, experimental, high-end, accessible, global, local. The Dark Ages feel impossibly distant.",keyDrinks:["aperol-spritz","naked-famous","penicillin"],keyFigures:["Contemporary bartenders at Dante, Analogue, Employees Only, and hundreds of other craft bars worldwide"],keyInnovation:"Low-ABV movement; mezcal as a cocktail spirit; clarified and centrifuged cocktails; fat-washing and spherification; sustainability and zero-waste bartending; the democratization of cocktail knowledge; global diversification of cocktail culture"}]},645,[]);
